In VBA (Visual Basic for Applications), OpenText usually refers to the Workbooks.OpenText method in Excel, which is used to open and parse a text file (such as .txt or .csv) into an Excel workbook with control over how the data is split, formatted, and interpreted.

It is not the same as OpenTextFile from the FileSystemObject — that one is for reading text files in VBA code, not for importing into Excel.

1. Workbooks.OpenText (Excel VBA)
This method lets you:

Specify the file path of the text file.
Define delimiter type (comma, tab, semicolon, etc.).
Set column data formats.
Choose encoding (via Origin parameter).
Control date formats and decimal separators.
Basic Syntax
Vba

Copy code
Workbooks.OpenText Filename, Origin, StartRow, DataType, TextQualifier, _
                   ConsecutiveDelimiter, Tab, Semicolon, Comma, Space, Other, _
                   OtherChar, FieldInfo, DecimalSeparator, ThousandsSeparator, _
                   TrailingMinusNumbers, Local
Example
Vba

Copy code
Sub ImportCSV()
    Workbooks.OpenText _
        Filename:="C:\Data\sales.csv", _
        Origin:=437, '437 = US encoding
        StartRow:=1, _
        DataType:=xlDelimited, _
        TextQualifier:=xlTextQualifierDoubleQuote, _
        Comma:=True
End Sub
This will:

Open sales.csv
Treat commas as delimiters
Start from row 1
Use double quotes as text qualifiers
2. OpenTextFile (FileSystemObject)
If you are reading text files directly in VBA code (not importing into Excel), you might use:

Vba

Copy code
Dim fso As Object, txt As Object
Set fso = CreateObject("Scripting.FileSystemObject")
Set txt = fso.OpenTextFile("C:\Data\notes.txt", 1) ' 1 = ForReading
MsgBox txt.ReadAll
txt.Close

